column1: Will the powers of the government of Myanmar cease to be held by the military before 1 October 2022?
column6: ['Leader Entry/Exit', 'Security and Conflict', 'Non-US Politics']
At the time making this predictions the last statement regarding this topic states that the military control has been extended until 2023 so the chances are slim to none.
I'm late to the forecast. But looking back, I would have forecasted the same thing.
Definitely no.

I don't think the powers of the government of Myanmar will be able to overthrow the military before October 1 2022. The Junta military force that has control of the government is a brutal force that will probably not step down peacefully. There is no evidence that the Junta has a crack or could potentially collapse. Although there are some plans in the works to overthrow the Junta, I doubt there will be efficient action taken before October 1.

The probability for this to happen now before October 1st which is in two days is extremely low. They would have to form a whole revolution and overthrow a military in crazy speed and time making this very unlikely.

The chances of a revolution to overthrow the military coup happening in 2 days is extremely improbable. Plus, the coup will not step down peacefully before then; they just extended their rule into 2023.

The idea of a Junta military coup on the government as legitimate is embedded in Myanmar's constitution. Occurrences such as this have happened in 2011 unless the military receives what is demanded. Due to this, unless an amendment happens ridiculously quickly, it is very unlikely Myanmar's government will be released.
General Min Aung Hlaing,s regime extended emergency military rule until 2023 because of last years coup.

I seriously doubt the powers would shift so fully so soon. In fact, the military extended its reign until 2023 as of August 1st. Supposedly they plan to hold "free and fair elections", yet that is highly doubted by its citizens and the international community.
its almost time
There is no indication a collapse of the militaries hold on government occurring in the next few days. It appears likely international intervention will be required to restore democracy to Myanmar.

Its entirely possible that resistance to Myanmar's junta will increase after their attack on a school they claimed housed rebels, but I do not believe that even if that is the case the government would fall in 6 days. I looked at the timelines from some Arab Spring overthrows and those took months, not days.
Truly doubt it will happen since its been in military rule for a while now and i don't think a big revolt (enough to switch powers) will happen by October 1

There has been no political movement or indication of a change, and there is less than two weeks until the end date, so there is an almost 0 chance that the government will reverse itself in such a short and sudden time period with no prior indicators.
hasn't happened yet

There is no evidence of a change in power in Myanmar anytime before October 1st, 2022. No action can occur so quickly giving it hardly any chance for a cease to be held by the military before October 1st.

While my prediction would be substantially higher if the timeframe extended further into the future, I do not believe the junta is so unstable that it will fall before the 1st. In fact, it seems to be taking steps to firm up its control by imprisoning dissenters. I only leave the 2% probability because uprisings can happen very quickly, and I do not feel certain yet that one will not happen. I intend to decrease this probability should nothing seem to be brewing in the next few days.

The military government of Myanmar continues to have a strong grip over the country. There is nothing to evidence a change by October 1 2022 given the effect of opposition groups recently in comparison to the control held by the government.

Since the coup started on 1 Feb 2021, the Military can effectively stay in power legally for 2 year. So, it is extremely unlikely that the military will cease before 1 Oct 2022. It becomes more likely following that, with a spike towards 31 Jan 2023 as this is when the period of military rule can no longer be claimed under law. After that, all bets are off :)

Going back down to 0% (from 1%, not a big change). Although there have been reports of the military struggling a bit, there is a wide gap between struggles and losing power. Even if there was serious pressure on the military (greater than there is now), there would most likely need to be extensive negotiations before the military loses power given that the military is supported by Russia and China (politically if nothing else). Thus, a transition of power would take the time that is in the order of months unless an actual coup against the military can take place, which is implausible (losing control of some territory would not be a coup or removing power from the military). This would put any resolution outside of this question's time frame.
maintaining current forecast

My base rate is one in 30 for something like this happening in general over two months. One possible world in which this happens is one in which a foreign organization like ASEAN negotiates an agreement for an aesthetic release of power. This would presumably be a challenge, but it's not exactly unheard of that a country can be run under the threat of military rule. The possibility that a foreign superpower like India or China steps in with economic sanctions is unlikely, but boosted by Myanmar's rich rare metal reserves. It seems like the optimal outcome for all parties is that Myanmar remains uneasy, with the threat of military rule looming, although India is historically content to let Myanmar be.

It is clear from swift and overwhelming execution of the coup, and the stability of the military regime since then that significant recourses and planning went into the government takeover, which suggests significant support within the armed forces, which strongly correlated with the concentration of wealth within the country. While there has been consistent public protest activity (which is highly impressive to have sustained over such a prolonged period), the protests lack a mechanism for accountability or influence over the government, and the widespread poverty within the country makes subsistence the highest or sole priority for a large percentage of the population, rendering them unable or afraid to participate in any action against the military government. The continued counterinsurgency/civil war provides a pretext for continued military control as a 'state of emergency', while also worsening the conditions for those impacted or displaced by the conflict. Given the limited time that Myanmar has been a democratic state compared to being military or colonially controlled means that democratic norms and checks/balances are not well entrenched within the country, making it easier for them to be overrode and warn down by junta control.

Thanks to the excellent research on base rates and analysis of @monicaflorio and @mattlerner, I am going to maintain my view from the last question on this subject. The most important factors to my view: 1) the military has set a date for elections in summer 2023, which is well after the deadline for this question 2) The military continues to enthusiastically kill their citizens to crush the rebels and sow fear among the non rebellious, a key factor in despots maintaining power in my view. 3) The rebels reportedly have no access to even basic heavy weapons to equal the government and no one seems to be stepping up to supply them. 4) New charges against ASSK. 5) The world’s attention is elsewhere and China cares a lot about stability on its borders with little care about democracy. 6) Military defector numbers are comparatively small and piecemeal.
No serious counter movement in the country currently exists to disrupt the individuals who have seized power and are likely now too corrupted to give any of it away.

The military regime is firmly entrenched and no viable opposition seems likely to arise in the near term. In the absence of a substantive shift in the conditions in the country (wrt independent judiciary, democracy), there doesn't seem to be a reason to believe that the Junta will abdicate any time soon.

The military is strongly entrenched, and it took them 12 years the first coup, and 23 years the second coup, to get round to holding sham elections. I assume that (nominal) independence of the judiciary comes along with the other two, and it's easier to just keep the state of emergency. The ongoing protests if anything make it less likely that the military will do anything different for now.
New charges placed on Aung San Suu Ki, protests still happening

Domestically I cannot see an opposition capable of organising, training, and equipping to displace the junta. Internationally, all efforts seem to be focused on the ASEAN, which seems to be negotiating with the junta and is unlikely to be rushed. With China's support of the junta able to ameliorate any sanctions, then it looks unlikely that we'll see a change in government before 1st October.

Domestically, it is hard to see a sufficiently well organised, trained and equipped challenge to the military junta that would see it relinquish its powers. Meanwhile, international work seems to be a) focused on restoring peace, human rights and halting the decline (as opposed to replacing the military), and b) channelled through the ASEAN network, which is prioritising stability and peace within the country, and seeking to establish this via the military junta. With China's support in the face of other international sanctions, it is hard to see any other route to change than the ASEAN discussions which, based on previous performance, won't be rushed.

There are a couple of scenarios in which question resolves yes: * Military is 'defeated' in some sense * Military voluntarily (and genuinely) decides to start sharing power * Military enacts some changes which give the illusion of power sharing (similar to 2011) I think first two possibilities are very low prob (<0.5% combined) Third is the more likely route to question resolving positive, however I'm still putting it as a low prob event (2% pick)

The military control the financial institutions. So unlikely to have miliatry give up powers of the government in the next several monnths. In the longer term, the military will establish a puppet government and officially cease to hold powers of the government. I anticipate this to occur by 2024.

Extremely unlikely. The military has shown no evidence of relenting on their campaign of repression of opposition protesters. China continues to do business in Myanmar and block further action at the United Nations even if offering half-hearted condemnations of some of the worst excesses. Western powers have no appetite for use of force to remove the military and many opposition leaders and organizers have been jailed.

The Median length for military regiemes is 10 Years. The most "fragile" phase for an Autocracy is when a leadership change happens. This could potentially happen in Summer as this is when Gen. Min Aung Hlaing. is supposed to age out as army chief, although the military have already handed governing power to him so this is unlikely. A Transition away from a military regime has shown to be safer for ousted leaders: https://chicagopolicyreview.org/2017/09/06/what-makes-military-dictators-transition-out-of-dictatorships/

The military has a strong grip on the economy and on the assets of the country. That is one big factor why the military will continue to hold power beyond OCt 2022. No new young dynamic opposition leader in sight.

Myanmar was under a military junta until 2011. It is unlikely that they will be so quick to give up power again with next to no international pressure and the former Nobel Peace prize winner in prison.

My sense is there is a very small, but non-zero, chance the military government will be deposed. Until the cost to the military pyramids of power are perceived by a high percent of the elements of the military, there will be little but cosmetic chance. As it has been for most of Myanmar's existence. Until international and domestic pressure builds significantly more, the current military leadership will remain. A more likely outcome is an internal shift in who in the military holds real power.

I'm going to shoot above the mean. Many coup d'etats elsewhere have led to (not necessarily democratic) elections in the following year, and it seems likely that this could be the same in Myanmar.

To get the outside view, I want to know for how many years a military regime is typically stable. It would be helpful to have a more global view, but in the interest of time, I'm going to narrow my view to Southeast Asia and to the time period after WWII.

Either the junta loses the civil war, very unlikely, or they rewrite the rules and jail their opposition so that their lapdog party can take over the government. They've given themselves until Aug 2023 to complete that project and hold another election, so it is also very unlikely to happen within 9 months.

The government of Myanmar has strong international backers (Russia and China), which precludes much activity on the part of international organizations like the UN. The military in Myanmar has the reputation of being very cohesive and of behaving as a unitary interest group, which gives it a strong staying power. It also has a long history of maintaining itself in power in spite of popular opposition. The civil opponents in cities are likely becoming worn out and the armed guerilla groups in ethnic enclaves do not appear to be very strong and probably have a difficult time finding international backers. It is going to be a long protracted fight that could last several more years.
